1 R Markdown

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents. For more details on using R Markdown see http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com.

When you click the Knit button a document will be generated that includes both content as well as the output of any embedded R code chunks within the document. You can embed an R code chunk like this:

summary(cars)
##      speed           dist       
##  Min.   : 4.0   Min.   :  2.00  
##  1st Qu.:12.0   1st Qu.: 26.00  
##  Median :15.0   Median : 36.00  
##  Mean   :15.4   Mean   : 42.98  
##  3rd Qu.:19.0   3rd Qu.: 56.00  
##  Max.   :25.0   Max.   :120.00

1.1 Including Plots

You can also embed plots, for example:

Note that the echo = FALSE parameter was added to the code chunk to prevent printing of the R code that generated the plot.

3 Equations

You can also create latex equations with cross referencing using the code as below:

$$
(\#eq:normal)
y_i \sim Normal(\mu, \sigma)
$$

Then you can link the equation in text in the same way as figures or tables \@ref(eq:normal). See the equation (3.1)

\[ \begin{equation} \tag{3.1} y_i \sim Normal(\mu, \sigma) \end{equation} \]

4 Extras

You can easily add extra functions to the rmd report, see the RMarkdown Cookbook.

4.1 Code download

Adding the code_download: true to the yaml allows to directly download the rmd file from the formatted html report. This is very useful on order to share a single file.

output:
  bookdown::html_document2: 
    code_download: true
